Toronto Raptors Nigeria-born president, Masai Ujiri, has been awarded a Doctor of Laws, Honoris Causa, from the University of Toronto, the institution announced last weekend. In Toronto, the 51-year-old  Zaria, Kaduna State-born ex-international is beloved as the architect behind the Raptors’ first NBA championship title while in Nigeria and Africa in general he is loved greatly for his contributions to the development of the game of basketball. Before he became the trailblazing president of a major-league basketball team, Ujiri was known as a passionate advocate for the role of sport to educate and enrich the lives of African youth.   Cech joins list of Chelsea departures     Mane gets jersey No. 17 at Bayern Munich     Ex- Nottingham legend tips Awoniyi for EPL  glory   Ujiri joined the Raptors organization in 2013 as executive vice president and general manager after winning the NBA Executive of the Year award with the Denver Nuggets. He was promoted to president of basketball operations three years later and in 2019 helped the Raptors win their first NBA title in franchise history. Ujiri also founded the non-profit organization Giants of Africa in 2003, currently conducting basketball camps in 10 countries and aiming to grow the sport across the continent with the focus of giving young players of both genders the skills to compete at an international level.